              "uri":"http://www.mendeley.com/research/italian-renaissance-diplomacy/",
              "eexcessURI":"http://www.mendeley.com/research/italian-renaissance-diplomacy/",
              "creator":"Michael Mallett",
              "description":"A renewed interest in Italian fifteenthcentury diplomacy and the publication of extensive sections of the diplomatic archives of the Italian states justify a new assessment of the significance of Italian Renaissance diplomacy. The conclusions of this essay are threefold, that Italian developments were less unique and less isolated from the European scene than used to be thought; that too much emphasis has been placed on a transition from occasional to continuous diplomacy; and that the emergence of the resident ambassador has to be seen in the context of changing decisionmaking mechanisms and bureaucratic structures. The differences between the diplomatic institutions and personnel of the princely and republican Italian states are particularly emphasized.",
